titleStmt.title: Cambridge, Cambridge University Library, MS Add.1124

respStmt.resp: Edited by Michael Marx in collaboration with Tobias J. Jocham et. al. TEI version created by Yasmin Faghihi and Huw Jones

summary.p: 96 folios; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: MS Add.1124; Qurʾānic text: Q 7:203-206, Q 8:1-7, Q 8:9-75, Q 9:1-114, Q 9:116, Q 10:1-7, Q 10:9-55; 8 Lines per page; Dimensions: 170 x 113 mm; Script style: kūfī D I; Estimated date of production: 9th or 10th century AD /3rd or 4th century Hijri.

Abbasid Qur'ān probably written in the third or fourth century A.H. / ninth or tenth century C.E, containing verses 203-206 from Sura al-Aʿrāf (سورة الأعراف) , the complete Sura al-Anfal (سورة الأنفال) and Sura al-Tawba (سورة التوبة), and verses 1-55 from Sura Yūnus (سورة يونس). For more information about the manuscript, see the entry in the Digital Library of Cambridge University.

The University of Cambridge acquired the fragment in 1878 from Edward H. Palmer (1840-1882) and E.E. Tyrwhitt Drake. The displayed fragment and other early Qur'an manuscripts (call numbers Add.1115 - Add.1150) were acquired by Palmer during a research trip to the Sinai Peninsula (cf. Ansorge 2016).
